=== USF40 / USF41 (2006) ===
In October 2005, Lexus premiered a gasoline-electric hybrid [[concept car]], the [[Lexus LF|LF-Sh]] (Lexus Future-Sedan hybrid), at the [[Tokyo Motor Show]] in Japan,<ref name=lfsh>{{cite web|url=http://www.theglobeandmail.com/servlet/story/RTGAM.20051124.wxwhlexus24/BNStory/specialGlobeAuto/|title=Lexus aims to conquer world|work=[[The Globe and Mail]]|accessdate=2009-02-22|last=Cato|first=Jeremy|date=2005-11-24}}</ref> publicly previewing the next Lexus flagship with a concept version for the first time. Introduced at the 2006 North American International Auto Show for the 2007 model year, the fourth generation Lexus LS became the first Lexus model to be produced in both standard and long-wheelbase versions. Based on the LF-Sh concept and using an all-new platform,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2007/10/12/MTGESN4CS.DTL|title=Lexus LS 460L: Redesigned sedan reaches new levels of luxury |work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] |accessdate=2009-02-15 |last=Voss|first=Arv|date=2007-10-12}}</ref> the LS 460 (USF40) uses the standard {{convert|2969|mm|abbr=on}} wheelbase, while the LS 460 L (USF41) features a stretched {{convert|3091|mm|abbr=on}} wheelbase.<ref name=lsfamilycar>{{cite web |url=http://www.familycar.com/RoadTests/LexusLS460/ |title=Familycar 2007 Lexus LS 460 Preview |accessdate=2007-04-08 |last=Ofria |first=Charles |publisher=FamilyCar.com |date=2006-08-30|quote=0-60: 5.4 sec.}}</ref> The fourth generation's technical specifications were shown in greater detail at the [[Geneva Motor Show]] in February 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.automobilemag.com/new_car_previews/2007/0605_2007_lexus_ls_460/index.html|title= New Car Previews: 2007 Lexus LS460|work=[[Automobile Magazine]]|last=DeMatio|first=Joe|accessdate=2009-02-14|date= 2006-06-05}}</ref> In 2008, all-wheel drive versions of the non-hybrid LS 460 and LS 460 L models were introduced at the [[Moscow International Motor Show]].<ref name=awd>{{cite web|url=http://www.autocar.co.uk/News/NewsArticle/Lexus-LS/234507/|title=Lexus LS460 gets 4x4|date=2008-08-19|work=[[Autocar]]|last=Parrott|first=Victoria|accessdate=2009-01-27}}</ref>

[[File:Lexus LF-Sh concept side.jpg|thumb|left|[[Lexus LF#LF-Sh|The Lexus LF-Sh]] concept at the 2005 [[Tokyo Motor Show]]]]

The LS 460 and LS 460 L are both equipped with a new 4.6&nbsp;liter ''[[Toyota UR engine#1UR-FSE|1UR-FSE]]'' [[V8]] producing {{convert|283|kW}} and {{convert|498|Nm|ftlbf}} of torque,<ref name=lsfamilycar/><ref name=production>{{cite web|url=http://www.autofieldguide.com/articles/090601.html|title=Lexus Comes Into Its Own|accessdate=2007-04-08|last=Vasiash|first=Gary|work=Automotive Design and Production|date=2006-08-30}}</ref> coupled to the first production eight-speed automatic transmission.<ref name=wcoty>{{cite web|url=http://www.autoblog.com/2006/01/08/lexus-ls-460-world-introduction-part-i/|title=Lexus LS 460: World Introduction|publisher=[[Autoblog]]|accessdate=2009-02-13|last=Arellano |first=Joel|date=2006-01-08}}</ref> The previous double-wishbone front suspension is replaced with a [[multi-link suspension|multi-link]] design.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roadandtrack.com/article.asp?section_id=6&article_id=3902|title=First Drive: 2007 Lexus LS 460 (10/2006)|work=[[Road & Track]]|accessdate=2009-05-21|last=Fr<U+00E8>re|first=Paul|date=2006-10}}</ref> To increase rigidity and lower [[upsprung weight]], [[forged]] [[aluminum]] is now used for the suspension links and steering knuckles,<ref name=sheetmetal>{{cite web|url=http://www.autonews.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/CW/20060821/FREE/60815003/1111|title=Behind the Sheetmetal - Inside the Lexus LS 460 and LS 460 L|work=Automotive News|accessdate=2009-05-21|last=Lyons|first=Peter|date=2006-08-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.carview.co.jp/road_impression/2006/lexus_ls460/04.asp|title=Lexus LS460 test drive|language=Japanese|publisher=Carview.co.jp|accessdate=2009-05-21|date=2006}}</ref> along with a single hollow [[machined]] [[die casting|die-cast]] aluminum front [[subframe]],<ref name=sheetmetal/> and approximately half of the body uses high-tensile steel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://subscribers.wardsauto.com/ar/lexus_flagship_tech/wall.html?return=http://subscribers.wardsauto.com/ar/lexus_flagship_tech/|title=Lexus Flagship Takes High-Tech Ground|work=Wards Auto|accessdate=2009-05-21|last=Schreffler |first=Roger|date=2006-12-28
}}</ref> Acceleration from 0<U+2013>{{convert|100|km/h|mph}} is listed at 5.7&nbsp;seconds.<ref name=LSEurope/> The LS 460 L matches the acceleration of the lighter LS 460 despite added curb weight,<ref name="LS 460 L Follow-Up Test, the Sleeper Phenomenon">{{cite web|url=http://www.edmunds.com/insideline/do/Drives/Followup/articleId=119408|title=LS 460 L Follow-Up Test, the Sleeper Phenomenon|accessdate=2007-03-05|last=Riches|first=Erin|publisher=Edmunds.com|date=2007-01-31}}</ref> at {{convert|40|kg|abbr=on}} more than the standard length model. 

The development of the LS 460 and its variants, led by chief engineer Moritaka Yoshida,<ref name=ls600hprod>{{cite web|url=http://www.autofieldguide.com/articles/060705.html|title=Feature Article - The Lexus LS 600H L: Not Just Another Production Car|work=Automotive Design and Production|accessdate=2009-02-15|last=Vasliash|first=Gary|date=2007-06}}</ref> began as Lexus was shifting its design strategy towards a more diversified product lineup,<ref name=dawson210>Dawson 2004, pp. 210<U+2013>211.</ref> with new vehicle launches largely focused on global markets.<ref name=dawson210/> Plans called for the next generation LS to differentiate itself further beyond previous models in terms of design and technology.<ref name=production/> A "Super LS" model, priced above the US$100,000 ultra-luxury category,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iht.com/articles/2006/04/16/business/Lexus.php|title=Lexus enters ultra-luxury arena|work=[[International Herald Tribune]]|accessdate=2009-02-22|2006-04|last=Maynard|first=Michelle}}</ref> was also considered.<ref name=dawson210/> Externally, the Lexus LS received the styling cues of Lexus' new design direction, called [[Lexus#L-finesse|L-finesse]].<ref name=design5>Newbury, Stephen. ''The Car Design Yearbook 5: The Definitive Annual Guide to All New Concept And Production Cars Worldwide.'' Merrell, 2006, pp. 162<U+2013>163. ISBN 1858943191.</ref> First shown on the LF-Sh concept, the vehicle gained body forms running the length of the car, [[wheel arch]]es, [[arrow]]-shaped [[chrome plating|chrome]] trim, a lower-set grille, and [[crystal]]line adaptive headlamps.<ref name=design5/> The long wheelbase LS 460 L possessed a similar profile as the LS 460, with identical overhangs in both front and rear, and longer rear doors. The forward and aft [[coefficient of lift]] was reduced to 0.02 and 0.01 respectively, while aerodynamic drag remained the same (''C''<sub>''d''</sub> 0.26).<ref name=nctdls460>{{cite web|url=http://www.nctd.com/review-intro.cfm?Vehicle=2007_Lexus_LS%20460&ReviewID=3691|title=2007 Lexus LS 460 Review|publisher=New Car Test Drive.com|accessdate=2009-02-15|last=McCraw|first=Jim|year=2006}}</ref>

[[File:Lexus LS 460 forward cabin.jpg|thumb|left|Fourth generation LS 460 cabin (USF40)]]

The LS 460 interior gained a push-button start, [[thin-film transistor]] instrument display, and numerous luxury options ranging from a hard disk drive-based GPS navigation system and song library to a heated steering wheel and [[XM Satellite Radio#Technology|XM NavTraffic]].<ref name=lsfamilycar/> The climate control offered the first [[infrared]] [[body temperature]] sensors and ceiling [[air diffuser]]s in an automobile.<ref name=engineering>{{cite web|url=http://www.sae.org/servlets/pressRoom?OBJECT_TYPE=PressReleases&PAGE=showRelease&RELEASE_ID=548|title=Automotive Engineering International Magazine Names Lexus LS 460 As 2007 Best Engineered Vehicle|Society of Automotive Engineers|date=2007-04-10|publisher=[[SAE International]]|accessdate=2007-05-06}}</ref> An "Executive" seating package on the LS 460 L included a rear seat DVD entertainment system, swivel tray table, and a [[shiatsu]] [[massage|massaging]] ottoman seat.<ref name=lsfamilycar/><ref name=lsprices/>

The addition of an [[Advanced_Parking_Guidance_System|automated parallel parking]] assist feature, the first of its kind in the U.S., allowed the LS 460 to steer itself into pre-selected parking spaces.<ref name=nctdls460/> Other drive assist features varied from a brake hold system to [[radar]] cruise control, electric [[power steering|variable gear ratio power steering]] and [[Electronically Controlled Brake|electronically controlled braking]].<ref name=lsfamilycar/> The new [[VDIM|stability control system]] was improved to anticipate skids and alter steering assist and gear ratios. The suite of new safety features extended from a eye-tracking [[Driver Monitoring System|driver monitoring system]] to a [[lane departure warning system]].<ref name=autobildsafety>{{cite web|url=http://www.autobild.de/test/neuwagen/artikel.php?artikel_id=12920|title=Auto Bild Safety Comparison LS460 vs. S550|accessdate=2007-04-09|work=[[Auto Bild]]|language=German|date=2006-12-05}}</ref><ref name=preventative>{{cite web|url=http://www.forbes.com/2008/11/14/smart-car-technology-forbeslife-cx_jm_1114cars.html|title=How Smart Is Your Car?|work=Forbes|accessdate=2009-02-22|last=Mitchell|first=Jacqueline |date=2008-11-14}}</ref> The pre-collision system added the first production [[image processing]] chip in a car capable of identifying vehicles and pedestrians in real time,<ref name=careye>{{cite web|url=http://www.journallive.co.uk/north-east-news/todays-news/2008/08/23/car-keeps-eye-on-road-and-on-you-61634-21589602/|title= Car keeps eye on road <U+2013> and on you|work=[[The Journal (newspaper)|The Journal]]|accessdate=2009-02-22|last=Lambell|first=Phil|date=2008-08-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://techon.nikkeibp.co.jp/article/HONSHI/20061113/123452/|title=New Toyota Lexus Detects Pedestrians, Applies Brakes |work=Nikkei Electronics|accessdate=2009-02-22|date=2006-11|last=Ooishi|first=Motoyuki}}</ref> along with [[radar|millimeter-wavelength radar]], stereo cameras, and infrared [[night vision]] projectors.<ref name=careye/> A rear pre-collision system with [[whiplash (medicine)|whiplash]]-preventing active seat headrests and dual-chamber front airbags were also introduced.<ref name=autobildsafety/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.detnews.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20060825/UPDATE/608250425|title=Rear collision warnings part of Toyota's safety features|accessdate=2007-04-08|last=Kageyama|first=Yuri|publisher=Associated Press|date=2007-02-11}}</ref>

[[File:2007 LS 460 L profile.jpg|thumb|right|The long-wheelbase Lexus LS 460 L (USF41)]]

The LS 460 and LS 460 L arrived at dealerships in Japan, the U.S., and Europe in late 2006,<ref>Lewin, Tony. (2006-02-05) "LS will lead a Lexus push into Europe." ''Automotive News Europe.''</ref> and the vehicle reached Australia, [[East Asia]], and the [[Middle East]] in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news.com.au/couriermail/story/0,23739,21870479-5010760,00.html|title=LS460: World<U+2019>s Best Car | |work=[[The Courier-Mail]]|accessdate=2009-02-15|date=2007-06-08|last=Hinchliffe|first=Mark}}</ref> The U.S. base price for the 2007 LS 460 and LS 460 L was US$61,000 and US$71,000, respectively.<ref name=lsprices/> From 2006<U+2013>2007, the average price paid for U.S. market LS 460 L sedans exceeded US$80,000, due largely to added options packages, placing the Lexus LS in the same average price range as its long wheelbase [[Audi]], BMW, and Jaguar rivals for the first time.<ref name=lsprices>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessweek.com/autos/content/feb2007/bw20070214_826825.htm|title=Lexus LS 460: More Luxury for Less|accessdate=2007-04-08|last=Peterson|first=Thane|work=BusinessWeek|date=2007-02-14}}</ref>

The 2006 [[Salone del Mobile|Milan Design Week]] exhibition at the Museo della Permanente in [[Milan, Italy]] featured an LS 460 concept with a sculpted body along with a [[fiber-optic]] "Evolving Fiber" landscape.<ref>
{{cite web|url=http://www.autoblog.it/post/3370/700-chilometri-di-fibre-nella-nuova-lexus-ls|title=700 chilometri di fibre nella nuova Lexus LS|publisher=Autoblog.it|accessdate=2009-02-24|language=Italian|last=Bassoli |first=Filippo|date=2006-04-07 }}</ref> Since 2007, a specialized Lexus LS 460 is used in a [[driving simulator]] at Toyota's Higashifuji Technical Center in [[Shizuoka, Japan]], for testing and development of automotive safety features. The vehicle is mounted inside a {{convert|4.5|m|abbr=on}} x {{convert|7.0|m|abbr=on}} high [[dome]] and surrounded by a 360<U+00B0> [[projector screen]], along with a strut- and track-mounted driver occupant dome containing the forward cabin of an LS 460.<ref name=Higashifuji>{{cite web|url=http://www.motoring.co.za/index.php?fArticleId=4146324&fSectionId=751&fSetId=381|title='World's biggest Playstation' tests safety systems|date=2007-11-26|publisher=Associated Press|last=Kageyama|first=Yuri|accessdate=2008-05-28}}</ref> Shown in 2009 at Tokyo's [[Intelligent Transport Systems]] (ITS-Safety) 2010 exhibition at the [[Miraikan]] museum, the LS 460 ITS-Safety concept included road-to-vehicle and vehicle-to-vehicle information-exchange technologies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edmunds.com/insideline/do/News/articleId=142412|title=Japanese Automakers Get Ready To Strut Advanced Safety Technology|publisher=Edmunds.com|date=2009-02-19|accessdate=2009-02-24|last=Lienert|first=Anita}}</ref>

=== UVF45 / UVF46 (2007) ===
{{main|Lexus LS Hybrid}}

[[File:Lexus-LS600h-L forward view.jpg|thumb|right|[[Lexus LS Hybrid|Lexus LS 600h L]] hybrid (UVF46)]]

After debuting a hybrid powertrain with the 2005 LF-Sh concept, Lexus launched the LS 600h L (UVF46), the first production V8-powered full hybrid vehicle, at the 2006 New York International Auto Show.<ref name=hybrid>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessweek.com/autos/content/apr2006/bw20060414_771632.htm|title=Lexus' New Luxury V8 Hybrid|accessdate=2006-12-01|last=Peterson|first=Thane|work=BusinessWeek|date=2006-04-14|2007-02-14}}</ref> Introduced in 2007 for the 2008 model year, the long wheelbase LS 600h L is equipped with [[Lexus Hybrid Drive]], featuring a 5.0&nbsp;liter ''[[Toyota UR engine#2UR-FSE|2UR-FSE]]'' V8 engine mated to a high-output electric motor with [[nickel metal hydride battery|nickel-metal hydride battery]] packs.<ref name=ls600hprod/> This system uses a [[continuously variable transmission]] and generates an output of {{convert|327|kW}}.<ref name=ls600hprod/> Fuel economy is slightly higher overall than the lower-powered non-hybrid LS, and the hybrids achieve a [[Super Ultra Low Emission Vehicle|Super Ultra Low Emission Vehicle (SULEV)]] rating.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2008/03/20/MTASVJL0C.DTL|title=2008 Lexus LS 600h L Hybrid Sedan: Environmentally friendliness meets high performance|work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]|accessdate=2009-02-15|last=Voss|first=Arv|date=2008-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.familycar.com/RoadTests/LexusLS600/|title=2008 Lexus LS600h L Road Test Review|last=Ofria|first=Charles|publisher=FamilyCar.com|accessdate=2009-02-15}}</ref> Features specific to the LS hybrids include the first production [[headlight#LED light sources|low beam LED headlights]], a leather-trimmed dash, and blue-tinted hybrid badging.<ref name=hybrid/> On April 6, 2007, Lexus announced that the base price for the LS 600h L would be over US$104,000,<ref name=ultraluxe>{{cite web|url=http://www.nextautos.com/countriesmarkets/japan/lexus-ls600hl-to-displace-toyota-century-as-japans-priciest-auto
|title=Japan Report: Lexus LS600hl To Displace Toyota Century As Japan<U+2019>s Priciest Auto|date=2007-05-08|work=[[Winding Road]]|accessdate=2007-10-01}}</ref> surpassing the [[V12]]-equipped [[Toyota Century]] as the most expensive Japanese luxury car ever produced.<ref name=ultraluxe/> A standard wheelbase version destined for Asia and Europe, the LS 600h (UVF45), was launched in Japan in April 2006.<ref name=ls600hlaunch>Karube, Takuya. (2006-11-19) "Toyota launches flagship LS sedan for Lexus brand in Japan." ''[[Kyodo News]]''.</ref>

In early 2007, specialty department store [[Neiman Marcus]] offered 100 individually-numbered LS 600h L "Launch Edition" sedans, available only through the Neiman Marcus catalog for InCircle members.<ref name=InCircle>{{cite web|url=http://www.edmunds.com/insideline/do/News/articleId=119074|title=Lexus Rolls Out LS 600h L Launch Edition Via Neiman Marcus|date=2007-01-04|publisher=Edmunds.com|accessdate=2008-05-28}}</ref> These models came in a separate Truffle Mica color with Alabaster interior.<ref name=InCircle/> For the 2007 Milan Design Week, an "Invisible Garden" exhibition at the city's Zona Tortona presented a frosted LS 600h hybrid model.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.repubblica.it/2007/04/motori/motori-aprile07/motori-design-lexus-milano/motori-design-lexus-milano.html|title=Lexus L-Finesse Invisible Garden nuova installazione artistica|language=Italian|work=[[La Repubblica]]|accessdate=2009-02-24|date=2007-04-21}}</ref> First shown at the 2008 Pebble Beach [[Concours d'Elegance]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autoblog.com/2008/08/15/monterey-2008-pebble-beach-edition-ls-600h-l-and-sc-430/|title=Monterey 2008: Pebble Beach Edition LS 600h L and SC 430|publisher=Autoblog|accessdate=2009-02-15|last=Lavrinc|first=Damon|date=2008-08-15}}</ref> the LS 600h L "Pebble Beach Edition" was produced in partnership with the [[Pebble Beach Company]], operator of the namesake golf courses and resorts. Limited to 50 units, these vehicles featured a two-tone interior with Pebble Beach badging and tags.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wot.motortrend.com/6284294/auto-news/2009-lexus-ls-600h-l-pebble-beach-edition-joins-sixth-sc/index.html|title=2009 Lexus LS 600h L Pebble Beach Edition joins sixth SC|date=2008-08-17|work=[[Motor Trend]]|accessdate=2008-06-21}}</ref>
{{clear}}

== Manufacturing ==
{{further|[[Tahara plant]]}}

[[File:Lexus CalSciCtr 1UZ-FE V8 exhibit.jpg|thumb|right|Lexus LS ''[[Toyota UZ engine|UZ]]'' V8 engine exhibit at the [[California Science Center]]]]

The Lexus LS has been consistently produced on dedicated Lexus assembly lines at Toyota's flagship Tahara factory,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://images.businessweek.com/ss/07/07/0712_makingof_lexus/index_01.htm|title=A Look Inside Toyota's Tahara Plant|work=BusinessWeek|date=2007-07|accessdate=2009-02-11|last=Rowley|first=Ian}}</ref> located in the city of Tahara in [[Aichi Prefecture]], [[Ch<U+016B>bu region]], southwest of [[Nagoya]], since 1989.<ref name=production/><ref>Tierney, Christine (2004-02-22). "Robot-filled Tahara sets standard for Toyota, world". ''[[The Detroit News]]''.<!-- http://detnews.com/2004/specialreport/0402/22/a15-70498.htm.-->Retrieved on 2007-05-06.</ref> Tahara remains the sole production site, having inaugurated its new line number four specifically for assembly of the original LS 400.<ref>Dawson 2004, p. 94.</ref> For the Lexus LS, the Tahara plant developed new molds and enhanced assembly techniques,<ref name=long25>Long 2001, p. 25.</ref><ref name=dawson92>Dawson 2004, p. 92.</ref> and instituted measures aiming to increase the precision of the sedan's fit-and-finish.<ref>Mahler 2004, p. 78.</ref> The 1989 LS 400 became the first production automobile to receive extensive [[laser welding]],<ref name=long25/> allowing for seamless steel welds.<ref name=dawson92/> A large [[sheet metal]] [[Stamping (metalworking)|press]] was developed to reduce or eliminate panel gaps by stamping large sections whole instead of singly.<ref name=dawson92/> Separately installed parts, such as exterior lights, were also [[spring loaded]] for a tighter fit.<ref>Dawson 2004, p. 90.</ref> On the LS 400, engineers reduced door panel gaps in half versus Toyota-brand vehicles, from {{convert|7|mm|abbr=on}} to {{convert|4|mm|abbr=on}},<ref name=dawson92/> with measurements made within {{convert|0.01|mm}};<ref name=edls430/> on the LS 430, measurement margins were increased tenfold to {{convert|0.001|mm|abbr=on}}.<ref name=edls430/><ref name=ls430production>{{cite web|url=http://www.autofieldguide.com/driven/0405dri21.html|title=Driven Article - 2005 Lexus LS 430|work=Automotive Design and Production|accessdate=2009-02-15|last=Vasilash|first=Gary|date=2005-04}}</ref> When production switched to the LS 460, the number of laser welds was doubled.<ref name=au>{{cite web|url=http://www.pressroom.com.au/press_kit_detail.asp?clientID=3&navSectionID=6&categoryID=1000&kitID=222#2235|title=LS460 Aerodynamics|publisher=Lexus.com.au|accessdate=2009-05-21|date=2007}}</ref>

Despite Tahara's large-scale automation, Lexus LS production also involves specialized personnel who are tasked with key production points, such as testing each vehicle's V8 engine via [[dynometer]] and [[stethoscope]] for calibration before installation.<ref name=production/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://lets.kumanichi.com/motornews/keizai/keizai134.HTML|title=Tahara plant line Lexus production|publisher=Kumanichi.com|accessdate=2009-05-02|language=Japanese|date=2007-06-28}}</ref> With the LS 460, a [[Orange peel (effect)|hand-sanded]] paint process was introduced.<ref name=production/> The production standards used on the Lexus LS were eventually adopted by the manufacturer for other vehicles; in 2007 the assembly of [[Toyota Corolla]] economy cars used the same panel gap measurements as the LS 400 did eighteen years earlier.<ref>Treece, James. (2007-07) "Obsession rules at Lexus flagship plant." ''Automotive News''.</ref>

== Industrial significance ==
[[File:Lexus Cutaway LS 400.jpg|thumb|right|LS 400 cutaway model displaying internal construction at the [[Wroughton]] [[Classic car|Classic]]]]

The Lexus LS marked the first successful entrant of a Japanese manufacturer into the [[prestige]] luxury arena,<ref name=whytoyota/> a market that had long been dominated by established European and American brands. By 1991, with the LS 400 its top-selling model,<ref name=dawson139>Dawson 2004, p. 137-41.</ref> Lexus had overtaken Mercedes-Benz and BMW in overall U.S. sales,<ref name=long57>Long 2001, p. 57.</ref> and in 2000 the marque passed [[Cadillac]] as the luxury sales leader in the largest automotive market.<ref>Dawson 2004, p. 7.</ref> Rival manufacturers responded with lower prices and added features.<ref>Dawson 2004, p. 147.</ref> In particular, Mercedes-Benz reorganized its operations, shifting to a targeted-cost process similar to Lexus production methods,<ref name=premium>Rosengarten, Philipp. ''Premium Power: Das Geheimnis Des Erfolgs Von Mercedes-Benz, BMW, Porsche Und Audi.'' Wiley-VCH, 2005, pp. 78<U+2013>80. ISBN 3527502173.</ref> and dropped competing U.S. base prices by nearly 10%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessweek.com/archives/1996/b3490132.arc.htm|title=The New Mercedes|date=2006-08|work=BusinessWeek|accessdate=2009-02-19|date=1996-08-26}}</ref> To rival the LS 400,<ref name=ls460effect>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.motortrend.com/6207600/auto-review/2007-lexus-ls-460-4053-miles/index.html|title=2007 Lexus LS 460|work=Motor Trend|accessdate=2009-02-19|last=MacKenzie |first=Angus|date=2007-04}}</ref> extra features were rushed for the launch of the 1991 [[Mercedes-Benz S-Class]] ([[Mercedes-Benz W140|W140)]],<ref name=premium/><ref>"Motoring" ''[[The Bulletin]]''. 1992-05. v. 5743-50, o. 49.</ref> causing budget overruns and costing the job of [[Daimler-Benz]] chief engineer Wolfgang Peter.<ref name=ls460effect/> Approximately five percent of 1989 LS 400 sales went to buyers employed by rival manufacturers, including [[General Motors|GM]], [[Ford]], and [[Chrysler]].<ref name=dawson139/> When the LS 400 was disassembled for engineering analysis, Cadillac engineers concluded that the vehicle could not be built using existing GM methods.<ref>May 2006, p. 47.</ref> Industry publications noted the LS 400's precise panel gaps, and the subject became a common evaluation standard in road tests.<ref name=ls460effect/> The LS 430's interior noise level was later used as a measure of cabin quiet.<ref>Egan, Peter. (2006-05) "Side Glances: Purr, Growl, Rattle, and Hum." ''[[Road & Track]]'', p. 48.</ref>

According to industry observers, the introduction of the Lexus LS reshaped Toyota's image from that of an "[[econobox]]" manufacturer to the builder of an automotive standard-bearer.<ref name=May42>May 2006, pp. 42<U+2013>43.</ref><ref name=comeback>{{cite book | last = Paul | first = Ingrassia | coauthors =White, Joseph | year =1995 | pages = 238 | title =Comeback: The Fall & Rise of the American Automobile Industry | publisher =Simon & Schuster |quote="...of such high quality that it had become the gold standard of the industry"| isbn =0684804379}}</ref> This stood in contrast to the predictions of early detractors, including rival manufacturers who dismissed Toyota as incapable of producing a competitive luxury vehicle.<ref name=comeback/> Japanese contemporaries from the luxury divisions of [[Honda]] ([[Acura]]) and [[Nissan]] ([[Infiniti]]) had differing degrees of success;<ref>Dawson 2004, p. 25.</ref> the mid-size V6-powered [[Acura Legend]] initially sold well, but subsequent models (renamed [[Acura RL]]) performed below sales expectations;<ref name=japaneseluxe>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessweek.com/autos/content/may2006/bw20060523_579325.htm|title=A Short History of Japanese Luxury Cars|work=BusinessWeek|accessdate=2009-04-13|last=Krebs |first=Michelle |date=2006-05-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.projo.com/projocars/content/ca_9acurarl_11-26-08_IABHKLK_v5.1e6969b.html|title=Acura<U+2019>s flagship sedan gets aggressive new look|publisher=Associated Press|accessdate=2009-04-13|last=Job|first=Ann|2008-11-26}}</ref> the V8-powered [[Infiniti Q45]] closely rivaled the LS 400 in specifications and price,<ref>Dawson 2004, p. 76.</ref> but was unsuccessful in sales, leading to its discontinuation in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edmunds.com/infiniti/q45/review.html|title=Infiniti Q45 Review|publisher=Edmunds.com|accessdate=2009-04-13}}</ref> The success of the Lexus LS became a test case for mainstream manufacturers targeting [[upscale]] segments; by investing in a separate marque, Toyota was able to avoid the stigma attached to a mass-market brand charging premium prices.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edmunds.com/news/column/carmudgeon/100398/article.html|title=Automotive Luxury 101 <U+2014> How to Create a Luxury Nameplate|publisher=Edmunds.com|accessdate=2009-04-14|last=Brauer|first=Karl|date=2003-07-31}}</ref> The effect of the LS 400 on the automotive industry led ''[[Automobile Magazine]]'' to name the sedan to its "24 Most Important Vehicles of the 20th Century" list in 1996.<ref>"24 Most Important Vehicles of the 20th Century." 1996-03. ''Automobile Magazine.''</ref>
{{clear}}

== Sales and production ==
[[File:Lexus Symphony Orchestra LS 460 series.jpg|thumb|right|LS 460 lineup filmed at [[Crystal Palace, London]]]]

In its largest market, the U.S., the Lexus LS was the top-selling flagship luxury sedan for 15 of the first 17 years following its debut.<ref name=wcoty/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stltoday.com/stltoday/autos/columnists.nsf/danwiese/story/FD30E9CD90032B6B8625729500768E73?OpenDocument|title=For well-heeled drivers who face parallel panic, Lexus LS 460 is the parking ticket|last=Wiese|first=Dan|work=[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]]|date=2007-03-11|accessdate=2007-04-10}}</ref> In Japan, the next largest market for the Lexus LS, the introduction of the 2007 LS 460 attracted 12,000 pre-orders,<ref name=Lexusjp>{{cite web|url=http://wardsdealer.com/latest/lexus_progressing_japan/|title=
Lexus Slowly Progressing in Japan|last=Schreffler|first=Roger|coauthors=Chrysler, Mack|date=2007-12-28|accessdate=2007-04-18|work=Ward's Dealer Business}}</ref> and the Lexus LS has gone on to sell successfully in its class.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edmunds.com/insideline/do/News/articleId=140230|title=Redesigned Lexus RX Unveiled in Japan|publisher=Edmunds.com|accessdate=2009-02-22|last=Nunn|first=Peter|date=2009-01-21}}</ref> Following the introduction of the LS 460 and Lexus' expanded global launch in 2007,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.busrep.co.za/index.php?fSectionId=&fArticleId=3981800|title= Revitalised Lexus puts luxury Toyota car brand on the map|work=Business Report (South Africa)|accessdate=2009-02-20|last=Cokayne|first=Roy|date=2007-08-14}}</ref> sales of the Lexus flagship have increasingly come from outside the brand's traditional U.S. strongholds. By 2007, the Lexus LS ranked second globally in flagship sales next to the Mercedes-Benz S-Class' 85,500 units, with 71,760 Lexus LS sedans sold worldwide,<ref name=LSglobal2007>{{cite web|url=http://online.wsj.com/article/SB121555041646936817.html?mod=hps_us_inside_today|title=Toning Down the 'Bangle Butt,' BMW Redesigns Its 7 Series|date=2008-07-09|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|last=Taylor|first=Edward|accessdate=2009-01-27}}</ref> and over half the total coming from outside the U.S. market.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theautochannel.com/news/2009/01/05/346214.html|title=Lexus 2008 sales figures|publisher=Autochannel|accessdate=2009-02-20|date=2009-01-05}}</ref> In 2008, U.S. sales fell 42% amidst the [[late-2000s recession]], mirroring the overall decline of the luxury car market.<ref name=amplify>{{cite web|url=http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601101&sid=aJNPURUsO0kg&refer=japan|title=Toyota<U+2019>s U.S. Pain Amplified by Falling Lexus Sales |publisher=Bloomberg|date=2009-04-06|last=Ohnsman|first=Alan|accessdate=2009-04-19}}</ref>

The Lexus LS has not sold as well in Europe, where Lexus suffers from smaller brand recognition, image, and a less-developed dealership network.<ref name=dawson194>Dawson 2004, pp. 194<U+2013>95.</ref> In European markets such as the [[Czech Republic]], the Lexus LS has ranked behind Mercedes-Benz, Audi, and BMW in flagship luxury car sales.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.auto.cz/cesky-trh/mercedes-benz-cesky-trh-v-roce-2008-nejprodavanejsi-luxusni-limuzinou-tridy-s.html|title=<U+010C>esk<U+00FD> trh v roce 2008: Nejprod<U+00E1>van<U+011B>j<U+0161><U+00ED> luxusn<U+00ED> limuz<U+00ED>nou |publisher= Auto.cz |accessdate=2009-02-20|date=2009-01-51|language=Czech}}</ref> Automotive analysts have suggested a possible rationale for the sales disparity, in that European buyers place less emphasis on vehicle reliability and have more [[brand loyalty]] to established domestic marques.<ref name=dawson194/> In contrast, the Lexus LS has ranked second in sales to the Mercedes-Benz S-Class, and ahead of rivals from BMW, Audi, and Jaguar, in markets outside Europe such as [[South Africa]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bizcommunity.com/Article/196/140/18890.html|title=Clever marketing boosts Lexus sales|publisher=BizCommunity.com|accessdate=2009-02-20|date=2007-10-16}}</ref>

